{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3538587,"name":"Mikiyas Asmamaw","username":"MikiA30","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/59ef9b/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-02-24T20:33:42.492Z","cooked":"<p>Hey, I’m essentially new to programming, having done it on and off but my town decided to make it’s very first robotics team in history and needed me to help them code. I’ve been learning day by day over the past month and we have a fully operating chassis that drives (using the Kraken x60 in a <span class="abbreviation">CAN<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Controller Area Network"></template></span> network) and we have an elevator now that we just put on yesterday. We had no encoders (only <span class="abbreviation">CIM<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Chiaphua Industrial Motor"></template></span> motors) but were lucky enough to stumble upon  one REV NEO motor which has a built in encoder. I downloaded the rev library and configured the motor controller. I added it to our current <span class="abbreviation">CAN<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Controller Area Network"></template></span> network, which hopefully it doesn’t matter that we are using Kraken motors and a REV in the same network. The issue was I wasn’t able to actually get the motor running. Now, that may have been because over half the day I had a faulty motor controller and thought my code was the problem but I tried reuploading the code after changing to a working motor controller and I wasn’t getting feedback. I used a template to start out which I found here, and I also heard that REV has updated its library this year. So it’s no longer CANSparkMax. I think now it’s just SparkMax when you code. I really don’t know where to start, and I haven’t actually had to code an encoder yet so if anyone has advice that would be great. I made a subclass called Elevator.java and did all the coding with the template someone posted on a forum and made adjustments too. I had Copilot help out some but it isn’t using the new updated library so it really wasn’t much help. Then in Robot.java I tried having the elevator go up certain heights as specified in the Elevator.java. I had no errors but it wouldn’t actually execute anything. I’ve just never delt with REV motors/Encoders before. I can easily tap into the <span class="abbreviation">PWM<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Pulse Width Modulation"></template></span> with other motors but never have had to use motors where I need to go into our <span class="abbreviation">CAN<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Controller Area Network"></template></span> network and use encoders. I have competition in a few days and the pressure is on if you can’t already tell. Let me know if you need the Robot.java file</p>
<p><strong>Here’s the elevator subclass I had</strong></p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">package frc.robot.subsystems;

import com.revrobotics.RelativeEncoder;
//import com.revrobotics.spark.SparkBase.PersistMode;
import com.revrobotics.spark.SparkLowLevel.MotorType;
import com.revrobotics.spark.SparkMax;
import com.revrobotics.spark.config.ClosedLoopConfig.FeedbackSensor;
import com.revrobotics.spark.config.SparkBaseConfig.IdleMode;
import com.revrobotics.spark.config.SparkMaxConfig;

import edu.wpi.first.math.controller.PIDController;
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command.SubsystemBase;

public class Elevator extends SubsystemBase {
    private final SparkMax elevatorMotor;          
    private final RelativeEncoder elevatorEncoder;  
    private final SparkMaxConfig motorConfig;

    private final PIDController pidController;        

    private final double COUNTS_PER_INCH = 42.0; 
    private final double GRAVITY_COMPENSATION = 0.1; 

    // Define target heights for scoring positions
    private final double LOW_GOAL_HEIGHT = 10.0; 
    private final double MID_GOAL_HEIGHT = 20.0;
    private final double HIGH_GOAL_HEIGHT = 30.0;

    private double targetHeight = 0.0; // Stores desired elevator height

    public Elevator() { 
      elevatorMotor = new SparkMax(13, MotorType.kBrushless); 
            motorConfig = new SparkMaxConfig(); 

            motorConfig
            .inverted(true)
            .idleMode(IdleMode.kBrake);

            motorConfig.encoder
            .positionConversionFactor(1000) 
            .velocityConversionFactor(1000); /

            motorConfig.closedLoop
            .feedbackSensor(FeedbackSensor.kPrimaryEncoder)  
            .pid(1.0, 0.0, 0.0); // Set PID coefficients


        elevatorMotor.configure(motorConfig, SparkMax.ResetMode.kResetSafeParameters, SparkMax.PersistMode.kPersistParameters);


        elevatorEncoder = elevatorMotor.getEncoder();  // Get encoder from the motor

        pidController = new PIDController(1.0, 0.0, 0.0); // Can be tuned for your system


        }


//         SparkMax max = new SparkMax(1, MotorType.kBrushless);
// SparkMaxConfig config = new SparkMaxConfig();


    /** 
     * Sets the desired elevator height in inches.
     */
    public void setHeight(double heightInInches) {
        targetHeight = heightInInches;
    }

    /** 
     * Runs the PID loop to move the elevator to the target height.
     */
    public void update() {
        double currentHeight = getHeight();
        double output = pidController.calculate(currentHeight, targetHeight) + GRAVITY_COMPENSATION;
        elevatorMotor.set(output);
    }

    /** 
     * Move the elevator to a specific scoring position based on the level
     */
    public void goToScoringPosition(int level) {
        if (level == 1) {
            setHeight(LOW_GOAL_HEIGHT);
        } else if (level == 2) {
            setHeight(MID_GOAL_HEIGHT);
        } else if (level == 3) {
            setHeight(HIGH_GOAL_HEIGHT);
        }
    }

    public void setSpeed(double speed) {
        elevatorMotor.set(speed);
    }

    public void stop() {
        elevatorMotor.set(0);
    }

    public double getHeight() {
        return elevatorEncoder.getPosition() / COUNTS_PER_INCH;
    }
}

